  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Prehospital initiated facilitation of primary percutaneous coronary intervention by
      fibrinolysis might be helpful in re-opening the infarct related artery prior to percutaneous
      coronary intervention.

      This studies tests the hypothesis that prehospital initiated facilitated PCI is superior to
      primary percutaneous coronary intervention with respect to infarct size.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      Patients with STEMI with symptoms &lt; 3 hours are randomized in the region of Leipzig to either
      prehospital full-dose fibrinolysis (+ASA, Clopidogrel and heparin) with subsequent
      facilitated percutaneous coronary intervention or to primary percutaneous coronary
      intervention (after ASA + heparin + clopidogrel).

      Patients undergo cardiac magnetic resonance for assessment of infarct size early at day 1-4
      after randomization.
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
